<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ900525-0055</DOCNO><DOCID>900525-0055.</DOCID><HL>   World Bank Clears   Loans to South Korea   For Research Projects</HL><DATE>05/25/90</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C10</SO><CO>   FREST LATAM AFRIC</CO><IN>BANKS (BNK)MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)</IN><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The World Bank cleared $76.6 million inloans to South Korea for technological research projects.   The bank said $45 million will go to universities and$31.6 million to several technology institutes, including theGenetic Engineering Center, which supports South Korea'sbiotechnology industry. Bank officials said the loans willhelp strengthen South Korea's capacity for technologicalinnovation, while reducing its dependence on importedtechnology.</LP><TEXT>   Other loans approved by the World Bank and its affiliate,the International Development Association, included theserecipients:   -- Rwanda, $40 million from the IDA for roads andtransport-sector projects.   -- Tanzania, $38.3 million from the IDA for primary andsecondary schools.   -- Caribbean Development Bank, based in Barbados, $32million from the World Bank and IDA, to help finance businessventures and other projects in a group of Caribbean islandcountries.   -- Colombia, $24 million from the World Bank to expandcommunity child-care and nutrition projects for preschoolchildren.   -- Central African Republic, $19 million from the IDA tohelp preserve forests and wildlife areas.   The World Bank loans carry a variable interest rate,currently 7.75% a year; the IDA credits will beinterest-free, except for administrative fees.</TEXT></DOC>